  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Merge Intervals\n\nMerge all overlapping intervals.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: intervals = [[1,3],[2,6],[8,10],[15,18]]\nOutput: [[1,6],[8,10],[15,18]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: intervals = [[1,4],[4,5]]\nOutput: [[1,5]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: intervals = [[5,7]]\nOutput: [[5,7]]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return the value described by the method signature.",
  "editorial": "Track the local choice that leaves the most room for future choices, or sort intervals so conflicts can be resolved with one pass.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def merge(self, intervals):\n        intervals.sort()\n        out = []\n        for start, end in intervals:\n            if not out or out[-1][1] < start: out.append([start, end])\n            else: out[-1][1] = max(out[-1][1], end)\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Sort first when relative order drives the decision.",
    "Keep the smallest state that proves future feasibility."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def merge(self, intervals):\n        pass\n"
  },
